  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. International Treaties and Conventions\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- These establish global standards and principles for anti-money laundering efforts\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries cooperate in investigating and prosecuting money laundering cases\n- Sharing of financial intelligence\n- Extradition agreements for financial crimes\n\n3. Regulatory Compliance\n- National laws must align with international standards\n- Banks and financial institutions required to implement specific reporting mechanisms\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) and Customer Due Diligence (CDD) protocols\n\n4. Jurisdictional Coordination\n- Cross-border investigations\n- Tracking international financial transactions\n- Identifying and disrupting money laundering networks\n\n5. Sanctions and Enforcement\n- International bodies can impose sanctions\n- Coordinated efforts to freeze assets\n- Prosecution of transnational financial crimes\n\n6. Information Sharing Mechanisms\n- Financial Intelligence Units (FIUs)\n- International databases and reporting systems\n- Real-time communication between national authorities\n\nThese intersections create a complex but interconnected system for combating money laundering globally.",
